#compdef cafeobj
# =============================================================================
# cafeobj — Toshimi Sawada's "CafeOBJ Interpreter" — the
#           canonical implementation of CafeOBJ, an algebraic
#           specification language descended from the OBJ
#           family (OBJ → OBJ2 → OBJ3 → CafeOBJ).  CafeOBJ
#           combines EQUATIONAL LOGIC (initial algebra
#           semantics), REWRITING LOGIC (dynamic / concurrent
#           behavior), HIDDEN ALGEBRA (object-oriented
#           specifications with observational equivalence),
#           and ORDER-SORTED TYPES (subsorting).
#           Distinguishing from Maude (Stanford OBJ
#           descendant), Coq / Lean / Agda (theorem provers
#           but not specification-first), and other formal
#           methods tools by:
#             - 4 LOGICAL FOUNDATIONS combined in one language:
#                 1. EQUATIONAL LOGIC — initial-algebra
#                    semantics with confluent rewriting
#                 2. REWRITING LOGIC — Meseguer-style state
#                    transitions for concurrent + non-
#                    deterministic systems
#                 3. HIDDEN ALGEBRA — Goguen's observational
#                    semantics for object-oriented
#                    specifications (states + behaviors)
#                 4. ORDER-SORTED TYPES — sort hierarchy with
#                    subsort relations (sub-types) +
#                    parameterized modules
#             - FLEXIBLE MIX-FIX SYNTAX — operators can have
#               arbitrary placement of arguments:
#                 op _+_  : Nat Nat -> Nat       -- infix
#                 op |_|  : Int -> Nat            -- circumfix
#                 op if_then_else_ : Bool A A -> A -- prefix
#               Underscores indicate argument positions;
#               whitespace separates the literal tokens
#             - PARAMETERIZED MODULES — modules can be
#               parameterized by theories (signatures with
#               axioms):
#                 mod! LIST(D :: TRIV) {
#                   [ D < List, Nil < List ]
#                   op _._ : D List -> List      -- cons
#                   op nil : -> List
#                 }
#             - VIEWS for module instantiation — map sort + op
#               names from theory to actual module:
#                 view NAT-EQ from TRIV to NAT {
#                   sort Elt -> Nat
#                 }
#             - PROOF SCORE METHODOLOGY — CafeOBJ's distinctive
#               approach: write proof scripts directly in the
#               specification language, run them with the
#               interpreter; specifications + proofs in one
#               file
#             - BIGPINK / PigNose EXTENSIONS — first-order
#               theorem prover extensions for proving
#               equational + Horn-clause theorems
#             - OBJ HERITAGE — direct descendant of OBJ (Joseph
#                Goguen, 1976), OBJ2 (1984), OBJ3 (1988),
#               which influenced Standard ML's module system
#               + Haskell's type classes; CafeOBJ adds Meseguer
#               rewriting logic + Goguen hidden algebra
#             - SBCL / ALLEGRO CL / CLISP RUNTIME — written in
#               Common Lisp; ships as standalone binaries
#               compiled with one of these Lisp implementations
#             - INTERACTIVE OR BATCH — default REPL prompt
#               `CafeOBJ>`; `-batch` flag runs scripts non-
#               interactively
#             - PARSE / MODEXP / IMPORT / MATCH / VIEW DEBUG
#               OUTPUT via `-parse-debug` / `-modexp-debug` /
#               `-import-debug` / `-match-debug` / `-view-debug`
#               for tracing different phases of specification
#               compilation
#             - LIBRARY PATH via `-l PATHS` or `-lib PATHS` —
#               colon-separated additional library directories
#               searched for `mod*` and `view*` definitions
#             - PRELUDE FILES via `-p FILE` or `-prelude FILE`
#               — pre-loaded specifications + theorems
#             - INDUSTRY APPLICATIONS — used by JAXA (Japan
#               Aerospace Exploration Agency) for spacecraft
#               software specification + verification; rail-
#               signal verification (Network Rail-equivalent
#               in Japan); banking system formal verification
#               in Germany (BSI-Bund BSI Federal Office for
#               Information Security uses CafeOBJ for PACE
#               protocol verification).
#           Used by: formal methods researchers at JAIST + Kyushu
#           University + Sannio University + BSI-Bund,
#           verification engineers preparing critical-system
#           safety cases (avionics, rail, banking, cryptographic
#           protocols), graduate education in algebraic
#           specification + rewriting logic, and as a reference
#           implementation of OBJ-family algebraic specification
#           in Common Lisp.
#
# Author:  CafeOBJ research community.  Original design by
#          Toshimi Sawada (Iwate Prefectural University +
#          JAIST Japan Advanced Institute of Science and
#          Technology), with contributions from Kokichi
#          Futatsugi (JAIST), Razvan Diaconescu (Romanian
#          Academy), Joseph Goguen (UCSD, posthumous), and
#          the broader CafeOBJ community.  Current version
#          1.6.0 (2020-01-20); maintenance continues at
#          cafeobj.org.  License: BSD-style (custom).
# Source:  https://github.com/CafeOBJ/cafeobj
#          https://github.com/CafeOBJ/cafeobj/blob/master/cafeobj/command-top.lisp
#          https://github.com/CafeOBJ/cafeobj/blob/master/cafeobj/cafeobj-top.lisp
#          https://cafeobj.org (official site, documentation,
#          binary downloads)
# Manpage: No manpage; documentation is the Reference Manual
#          at https://cafeobj.org/files/manual/.
# Language: CafeOBJ (https://cafeobj.org).  Distinct from:
#              * OBJ3 (Goguen + Tracz; CafeOBJ's direct
#                ancestor; pure equational logic)
#              * Maude (Meseguer; Stanford OBJ3 fork; also
#                rewriting logic but no hidden algebra)
#              * Larch (J. Guttag; algebraic spec with two-tier
#                approach)
#              * Casl (Common Algebraic Specification
#                Language; standardization effort)
#              * SOS (Plotkin's Structural Operational
#                Semantics; framework not implementation)
#              * Coq / Lean / Agda (theorem provers; not
#                specification-first)
#          CafeOBJ distinguishes itself by:
#             1. COMBINING 4 LOGICS — equational + rewriting +
#                hidden + order-sorted in ONE language
#             2. PROOF SCORE METHODOLOGY — proofs in the
#                language itself (not external)
#             3. PARAMETERIZED MODULES with VIEWS — Goguen-
#                style theory-of-modules
#             4. ORDER-SORTED TYPES with subsort relations
#             5. MIX-FIX SYNTAX
#             6. HIDDEN ALGEBRA — only major specification
#                language with first-class hidden sorts
#             7. JAIST + Toshimi Sawada provenance
#             8. INDUSTRY ADOPTION — JAXA / BSI-Bund / rail
#                safety
#             9. OBJ-FAMILY HERITAGE — 50+ years of algebraic
#                specification language research (OBJ 1976)
#            10. COMMON LISP IMPLEMENTATION — bootstrappable
#                on SBCL / Allegro CL / CLISP
# License: BSD-style (custom)
# Status:  41+ stars on CafeOBJ/cafeobj; current version
#          1.6.0 (2020); maintenance + community contributions
#          continue.  cafeobj.org is the canonical reference
#          site.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 103RD LANGUAGE: CAFEOBJ
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy expands its
# **103RD PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE**: CafeOBJ.  This expands the taxonomy from
# 102 to 103 documented programming languages.
#
# Pattern: R681 Rust=78 (jsonschema → Axis 23 OPENS) → R682 Go=78
# (santhosh-tekuri/jsonschema) → R683 TS-Node=78 (ajv → Axis 23 1/1/1)
# → R684 103RD LANGUAGE (CafeOBJ via cafeobj THIS).  This completes
# the 3-leader-bump + 1-new-language micro-cycle.
#
# WHY CAFEOBJ IS A DISTINCTIVE 103RD LANGUAGE:
#
#   1. ALGEBRAIC SPECIFICATION PARADIGM — CafeOBJ belongs to
#      the ALGEBRAIC SPECIFICATION language family, distinct
#      from every previously-documented language in the
#      taxonomy.  Algebraic specs describe abstract data types
#      via SORTS + OPERATIONS + EQUATIONS; semantics determined
#      by INITIAL ALGEBRA (smallest model satisfying the
#      axioms).  Distinct from:
#        - Imperative (Python, Ruby, Java, C)
#        - Functional (Haskell, OCaml, F#, Lisp)
#        - Logic (Prolog, Mercury, Logtalk, Picat, Curry)
#        - Probabilistic (Stan — R676)
#        - Theorem provers (Coq, Lean, Agda, Idris,
#                            Dafny — all in taxonomy)
#        - Constraint (MiniZinc / GNU MathProg)
#      Algebraic specification is a NEW paradigm in the
#      taxonomy.
#
#   2. 4 LOGICAL FOUNDATIONS COMBINED — CafeOBJ uniquely
#      combines EQUATIONAL + REWRITING + HIDDEN + ORDER-
#      SORTED logics in one language.  Distinct from:
#        - Maude:    equational + rewriting (no hidden)
#        - OBJ3:     equational only
#        - Casl:     equational + first-order (no rewriting)
#        - Tools using only HOL (Coq/Lean/Agda):
#                    no equational/rewriting/hidden focus
#      The 4-logic combination enables CafeOBJ to specify
#      systems with both static (equational) and dynamic
#      (rewriting) aspects, plus object-oriented (hidden)
#      and subtyping (order-sorted).
#
#   3. PROOF SCORE METHODOLOGY — CafeOBJ's distinctive
#      proof methodology: proofs are written DIRECTLY IN
#      THE SPECIFICATION LANGUAGE as case-split + induction
#      scripts.  Specifications + proofs share one file.
#      Distinct from external theorem provers (Coq tactics,
#      Lean tactic blocks) which separate proof scripts
#      from specifications.
#
#   4. PARAMETERIZED MODULES with VIEWS — CafeOBJ inherited
#      OBJ's parameterized-module system.  A theory TRIV
#      (trivial theory with one sort) parameterizes generic
#      modules:
#         mod* TRIV { [Elt] }
#         mod! LIST(D :: TRIV) { ... }
#         view NAT-EQ from TRIV to NAT { sort Elt -> Nat }
#         mod NAT-LIST = LIST(NAT-EQ).
#      Goguen's theory-of-modules architecture directly
#      influenced Standard ML's module system + Haskell's
#      type classes.
#
#   5. ORDER-SORTED TYPES — subsort relations between sorts:
#         [ Nat < Int < Rat < Real < Complex ]
#         op _+_ : Real Real -> Real
#         -- 5 : Nat, 5 + 3.14 = 8.14 : Real (auto-widening)
#      Distinct from un-sorted (Lisp, Smalltalk), single-
#      sorted (Prolog), and multi-sorted-without-subsorts
#      (most functional languages).
#
#   6. MIX-FIX SYNTAX — operator placement is fully
#      configurable via underscore-marked positions:
#         op _+_         : Nat Nat -> Nat       -- infix
#         op |_|         : Int -> Nat            -- circumfix
#         op if_then_else_ : Bool A A -> A      -- mix-fix
#         op _._         : List List -> List     -- infix concat
#         op nil         : -> List               -- nullary
#      Operators look like the mathematical notation; CafeOBJ
#      specifications read like textbook mathematics.
#
#   7. HIDDEN ALGEBRA / OBSERVATIONAL EQUIVALENCE — Goguen's
#      contribution to OOP semantics.  Hidden sorts represent
#      object states; observational equivalence: two states
#      are equivalent iff all observations (method invocations)
#      return equal results:
#         mod* COUNTER {
#           *[ Counter ]    -- * = hidden sort
#           bop value   : Counter -> Nat     -- observer
#           bop inc     : Counter -> Counter -- action
#           eq value(inc(C)) = value(C) + 1
#         }
#      Distinct from class-based OOP semantics in
#      mainstream languages.
#
#   8. BIGPINK / PigNose THEOREM PROVING EXTENSIONS —
#      first-order resolution-style theorem prover built
#      into CafeOBJ for proving equational + Horn-clause
#      theorems.  --with-pignose at build time enables
#      the extensions.
#
#   9. JAIST + JAPAN INDUSTRY ADOPTION — CafeOBJ is
#      maintained at JAIST (Japan Advanced Institute of
#      Science and Technology); used by JAXA (Japan
#      Aerospace) for spacecraft software verification +
#      Japanese railway safety verification + cryptographic
#      protocol verification.
#
#  10. OBJ-FAMILY 50+ YEAR HISTORY — direct descendant of
#      OBJ (Joseph Goguen, 1976) through OBJ2 (Goguen +
#      Futatsugi, 1984) and OBJ3 (1988).  CafeOBJ refines
#      OBJ3 with rewriting logic + hidden algebra.  50+
#      years of algebraic specification research lineage.
#
# Cross-language CLI library taxonomy after R684:
#   * 103 LANGUAGES DOCUMENTED (CafeOBJ is the 103rd)
#   * 413 total CLI library variants
#   * Rust=78 / Go=78 / TS-Node=78 (three-way tie at leaderboard top)
#   * Axis 9 / Logging: 6/6/6 three-language symmetric
#   * Axes 10 + 13 + 14: 2/2/2 three-language symmetric
#   * Axes 7 + 8 + 11 + 12 + 15 + 16 + 17 + 18 + 19 + 20 + 21
#     + 22 + 23 at 1/1/1 three-language symmetric
#   * Sixteen axes at three-language symmetry
#
# Algebraic specification family in taxonomy:
#   * cafeobj (THIS, R684) — CafeOBJ (4-logic combo)
#   * maude (R???) — Maude (equational + rewriting; Stanford
#                    OBJ3 fork)
#   Both belong to the OBJ-family algebraic specification
#   tradition founded by Joseph Goguen in 1976.
#
# Languages documented prior to R684 (selected):
#   * R672 Cpp2 (cppfront) — 100th [MILESTONE]
#   * R676 Stan (stanc) — 101st [first post-100]
#   * R680 SETL (setl) — 102nd
#   * R684 CafeOBJ (cafeobj THIS) — 103rd
